The potentials factorize according to the features{fk} and weights{λk} of G as:
Φ`(y`,t, y`,t+1,x, t) = exp {∑ k λkfk(y`,t, y`,t+1,x, t) }
Ψ`(y`,t, y`+1,t,x, t) = exp {∑ k λkfk(y`,t, y`+1,t,x, t) }
More complicated structures are also possible, such as semi-Markov CRFs, in which the state transition probabilities depend on how long the chain has been in its current state, and hierarchical CRFs, which are moralized versions of the hierarchical HMMs of Fine et al. (1998).1 As in DBNs, this factorized structure can use many fewer parameters than the cross-product state space: even the two-level FCRF we discuss below uses less than an eighth of the parameters of the corresponding cross-product CRF.
1Hierarchical HMMs were shown to be DBNs by Murphy and Paskin (2001).

